Consider this TypeScript code:

```typescript
class Counter {
  count = 0;
}

const a = new Counter();
const b = new Counter();
a.count = 5;
```

After this code runs, `b.count` is still `0`.

Consider this TypeScript code:

```typescript
class Shape {
  draw(): string {
    return "shape";
  }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  draw(): string {
    return "circle";
  }
}

class Square extends Shape {
  draw(): string {
    return "square";
  }
}
```

Which object-oriented concept is shown by `Circle` and `Square` providing different versions of `draw()`?

